**Elasticsearch version**: 7.8.0
**Description of the problem including expected versus actual behavior**:
Data frame analytics jobs fails when the destination index exists. But the documentation says:
"If the destination index exists, it is used as is. You can therefore set up the destination index in advance with custom settings and mappings."

**Steps to reproduce**:
Run in Dev Tools Console

POST test-source-index-a2/_doc
{"value1": 1, "target": 1}

POST test-source-index-a2/_doc
{"value1": 2, "target": 4}

POST test-source-index-a2/_doc
{"value1": 3, "target": 9}

PUT test-dest-index-a2

PUT _ml/data_frame/analytics/test-dfa-job-a2
{
  "description": "",
  "source": {
    "index": "test-source-index-a2"
  },
  "dest": {
    "index": "test-dest-index-a2"
  },
  "analyzed_fields": {
    "excludes": []
  },
  "analysis": {
    "regression": {
      "dependent_variable": "target"
    }
  },
  "model_memory_limit": "20mb"
}

POST _ml/data_frame/analytics/test-dfa-job-a2/_start

-> Kibana Machine Learning / Data Frame Analytics shows status "failed"

**Provide logs (if relevant)**:

There are two different scenarios where this fails, both with the same output. The query used is the same in both cases:
```
{
  "query": {
    "match_all": {}
  },
  "fields": [
    "*"
  ]
}
```

Also, the output is almost the same in both cases, with the exception of the input string being formatted:

```
{
    "error": {
        "root_cause": [
            {
                "type": "number_format_exception",
                "reason": "For input string: \"[[1, 2]]\""
            }
        ],
        "type": "search_phase_execution_exception",
        "reason": "all shards failed",
        "phase": "query",
        "grouped": true,
        "failed_shards": [
            {
                "shard": 0,
                "index": "test",
                "node": "UysFGHdVSiiHtIR9UgkWmg",
                "reason": {
                    "type": "number_format_exception",
                    "reason": "For input string: \"[[1, 2]]\""
                }
            }
        ],
        "caused_by": {
            "type": "number_format_exception",
            "reason": "For input string: \"[[1, 2]]\"",
            "caused_by": {
                "type": "number_format_exception",
                "reason": "For input string: \"[[1, 2]]\""
            }
        }
    },
    "status": 400
}
```

1. `{"a" : {"b" : [[[1,2]]]}}` error message reason is `"reason": "For input string: \"[[1, 2]]\""`
2. `{"a" : [{"b" : [1,2]}]}` error message reason is `"reason": "For input string: \"[1, 2]\""`

The tests above are for numbers, but for strings there is semi-faulty behavior as well. For a document containing `{"a" : [{"b" : [["x","y"]]}]}` the output of `fields` for `a.b` and `a.b.keyword` is `"[[x, y]]"` I would have expected an array of string values not a string value representing two nested arrays with the two values as a single one.

CC @jtibshirani

Index names for data streams are recognized by EQL, both with the hidden backed indices as well as the full name. But index _patterns_ are not.

Create the data stream
``` javascript
PUT /_index_template/my-data-stream-template
{
  "index_patterns": [ "my-data-stream*" ],
  "data_stream": { }
}
```

Add a document
```javascript
POST /my-data-stream/_doc/?refresh=wait_for
{
  "@timestamp": "2020-12-06T11:04:05.000Z",
  "process": {
    "name": "cmd.exe"
  },
  "event": {
    "category": "process"
  }
}
```
```javascript
POST /my-data-stream/_rollover
```

Search the data stream by the full name
```javascript
GET /my-data-stream/_eql/search
{
  "query": "process where process.name == \"cmd.exe\""
}

// returns this result
{
  "is_partial" : false,
  "is_running" : false,
  "took" : 1,
  "timed_out" : false,
  "hits" : {
    "total" : {
      "value" : 1,
      "relation" : "eq"
    },
    "events" : [
      {
        "_index" : ".ds-my-data-stream-000001",
        "_type" : "_doc",
        "_id" : "L3ouxHMBxE7N-EVkNADM",
        "_score" : null,
        "_source" : {
          "@timestamp" : "2020-12-06T11:04:05.000Z",
          "process" : {
            "name" : "cmd.exe"
          },
          "event" : {
            "category" : "process"
          }
        },
        "fields" : {
          "@timestamp" : [
            "1607252645000"
          ]
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}
```

Search the index pattern
```javascript
GET /my-data-stream*/_eql/search
{
  "query": "process where process.name == \"cmd.exe\""
}

// get this result
{
  "error" : {
    "root_cause" : [
      {
        "type" : "index_not_found_exception",
        "reason" : "no such index [my-data-stream*]",
        "index_uuid" : "_na_",
        "index" : "my-data-stream*"
      }
    ],
